---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'horowitz-crater');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Horowitz Crater location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Horowitz Crater RSL - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900 to-teal-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Dark seasonal streaks flowing down crater slopes in Horowitz Crater
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/University of Arizona</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Horowitz Crater stands out as one of Mars' most intriguing locations 
          for studying recurring slope lineae (RSL) - mysterious dark streaks 
          that appear and disappear seasonally on crater slopes. These enigmatic 
          features have captured the attention of planetary scientists as potential 
          evidence of contemporary water activity on Mars, representing some of 
          the most dynamic geological processes currently observable on the planet.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The crater's steep slopes, ranging from 25° to 40°, provide ideal 
          conditions for RSL formation during Mars' warmest seasons. These narrow 
          features, typically 0.5 to 5 meters wide, exhibit distinctive dark 
          markings that incrementally grow during warm periods and fade during 
          cold seasons, showing a strong correlation with solar heating and 
          surface temperatures.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          What makes Horowitz Crater particularly significant is the spectral 
          evidence for hydrated salts detected on these slopes, supporting 
          hypotheses about briny water involvement in RSL formation. However, 
          recent studies have sparked scientific debate about whether these 
          features represent active liquid water processes or dry granular flows.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">RSL Width:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">0.5 - 5 meters</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Slope Angle:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">25° - 40°</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Active Season:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Late spring to summer</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Temperature Range:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">-23°C to 27°C</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Detected Salts:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Perchlorates, chlorates</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RSL Formation and Characteristics Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Recurring Slope Lineae: Mars' Dynamic Features
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Recurring slope lineae at Horowitz Crater represent some of the most 
        dynamic geological features currently active on Mars. These seasonal 
        phenomena demonstrate a clear correlation with temperature cycles, 
        appearing during the warmest months and fading during cooler periods, 
        suggesting ongoing physical processes in the near-surface environment.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Formation Characteristics</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            RSL exhibit slow incremental growth, appearing first as small dark 
            patches that gradually extend downslope over the course of weeks to 
            months. They favor equator-facing slopes that receive maximum solar 
            heating, with peak activity correlating with surface temperatures 
            reaching their seasonal maximum.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Seasonal Behavior</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The features demonstrate remarkable seasonal fidelity, with annual 
            fading and recurrence patterns that have been observed across multiple 
            Martian years. This predictable behavior suggests a repeatable 
            physical process tied to environmental conditions rather than random 
            geological events.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Water Evidence and Spectral Analysis Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Evidence for Briny Water Activity
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-cyan-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Hydrated Salt Detection
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Spectroscopic analysis using the Compact Reconnaissance Imaging 
          Spectrometer (CRISM) has detected hydrated salts on RSL slopes at 
          Horowitz Crater. The salts most consistent with spectral features 
          include magnesium perchlorate, magnesium chlorate, and sodium perchlorate.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          These findings strongly support the hypothesis that RSL form as a 
          result of contemporary water activity, as these salts would likely 
          require liquid water for their formation and preservation in the 
          observed hydrated state.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-teal-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Brine Formation Mechanisms
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The detected perchlorate salts can significantly lower the freezing 
          point of water, allowing liquid brines to exist at temperatures well 
          below pure water's freezing point. This property makes them ideal 
          candidates for enabling liquid water activity in Mars' current climate.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Proposed mechanisms include deliquescence, where atmospheric water 
          vapor is absorbed by salt crystals to form liquid solutions, or 
          interactions between different salt types that produce landslide-triggering 
          chemical reactions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Contemporary Water Activity Evidence
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The combination of seasonal behavior, temperature correlation, and 
        hydrated salt detection provides compelling evidence for contemporary 
        water activity at Horowitz Crater. While the actual volumes of liquid 
        water involved may be very small, the implications for understanding 
        current Martian processes are significant.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        This evidence suggests that Mars is not as geologically inactive as 
        previously thought, with ongoing processes that could provide insights 
        into the planet's current habitability potential and water cycle dynamics.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Debate Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      The RSL Formation Debate
    </h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          While initial interpretations of RSL strongly favored liquid water 
          processes, the scientific community continues to debate their exact 
          formation mechanisms. Recent studies have proposed alternative 
          explanations involving dry granular flows, challenging the water-based 
          models and highlighting the complexity of these features.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Liquid Water Hypothesis
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Brines from subsurface aquifers or atmospheric processes create 
              sufficient water activity to mobilize surface materials.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-orange-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Dry Flow Hypothesis
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Temperature-triggered dry granular flows involving dust and fine 
              particles, without requiring liquid water.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
            <h4 class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">
              Hybrid Mechanisms
            </h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
              Combination processes involving minimal water activity that 
              triggers larger-scale dry granular movements.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Current Research Focus
        </h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Spectral Analysis:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Ongoing</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Laboratory Studies:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Active</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Modeling:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Comparative</span>
          </div>
          <div class="flex justify-between">
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Monitoring:</span>
            <span class="text-white text-sm">Multi-year</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Planetary Protection Implications Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Planetary Protection and Habitability
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/50 to-teal-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Special Regions Classification
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Due to the potential involvement of liquid water, RSL sites like 
          Horowitz Crater are classified as "Uncertain Regions, to be treated 
          as Special Regions" under planetary protection guidelines. This 
          classification recognizes that these areas might harbor conditions 
          where Earth life could potentially survive.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          This designation requires special precautions for any future missions 
          to these areas to prevent forward contamination and preserve the 
          integrity of potential Martian biological processes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/50 to-indigo-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Habitability Assessment
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          While the brines associated with RSL may be too cold or too salty 
          for most Earth life, they represent some of the most potentially 
          habitable environments currently known on Mars. The combination of 
          liquid water (even if briny) and seasonal activity suggests dynamic 
          chemical processes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          These conditions might support extremophile organisms adapted to 
          high-salt, low-temperature environments, similar to organisms found 
          in Earth's most extreme environments.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Assessment Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-yellow-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-yellow-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-yellow-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">7</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Good Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-yellow-300">
            Active water processes and diverse geological features
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Evidence of contemporary water activity</li>
            <li>• Hydrated salt deposits for resource extraction</li>
            <li>• Seasonal process understanding for prediction</li>
            <li>• Diverse slope environments for habitat placement</li>
            <li>• Active geological processes</li>
            <li>• Potential subsurface water sources</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Extremely saline water conditions</li>
            <li>• Limited water volumes</li>
            <li>• Steep terrain navigation difficulties</li>
            <li>• Seasonal temperature extremes</li>
            <li>• Planetary protection restrictions</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation issues</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Significance Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Significance
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Contemporary Mars Processes
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Horowitz Crater's RSL provide crucial insights into currently active 
          geological and potentially hydrological processes on Mars. Understanding 
          these features helps scientists determine whether Mars remains 
          geologically and hydrologically active, with implications for current 
          habitability and future human exploration strategies.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Astrobiology Research
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          As one of the few locations on Mars with potential contemporary liquid 
          water activity, Horowitz Crater represents a prime target for 
          astrobiology research. The site offers opportunities to study how 
          life might survive in extreme saline, low-temperature conditions 
          and to search for biosignatures in currently active environments.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Opportunities
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Horowitz Crater represents a high-priority target for future Mars 
        exploration, particularly for missions focused on astrobiology and 
        understanding contemporary Martian processes. However, its classification 
        as a Special Region requires careful mission planning to meet planetary 
        protection requirements.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Research Priorities
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• In-situ RSL formation monitoring</li>
            <li>• Subsurface water detection</li>
            <li>• Salt deposit detailed analysis</li>
            <li>• Seasonal process characterization</li>
            <li>• Life detection experiments</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Mission Considerations
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Planetary protection compliance</li>
            <li>• Sterilization requirements</li>
            <li>• Remote sensing capabilities</li>
            <li>• Multi-season monitoring</li>
            <li>• Sample containment protocols</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Research</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nature.com/articles/ngeo2546"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Spectral Evidence for Hydrated Salts (Nature)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0032063322000290"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Multiband Photometry of RSL at Horowitz
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6443380/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Deep Groundwater Origin for RSL
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/resource/recurring-lineae-on-slopes-at-horowitz-crater"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              NASA RSL Resource Page
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/resources/3588/warm-season-flows-on-slope-in-horowitz-crater-eight-image-sequence/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              RSL Image Sequence Documentation
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seasonal_flows_on_warm_Martian_slopes"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Seasonal Flows on Mars - Wikipedia
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>